title: Loreta Kullashi
text:
Loreta Kullashi (born 20 May 1999) is a Swedish <a href="Association%20football">football</a> <a href="Forward%20%28association%20football%29">forward</a> who plays for Swedish club <a href="FC%20Roseng%C3%A5rd">FC Rosengård</a> in the <a href="Damallsvenskan">Damallsvenskan</a> and the <a href="Sweden%20women%27s%20national%20football%20team">Sweden national team</a>.
Club career.
Kullashi was born in <a href="Helsinki">Helsinki</a>, Finland, to <a href="Albanians%20in%20Kosovo">Kosovar-Albanian</a> parents. She moved to Sweden from Finland when she was five years old, and she grew up in <a href="Halmstad">Halmstad</a>. She started playing organised football with <a href="Sn%C3%B6storp%20Nyhem%20FF">Snöstorp Nyhem FF</a>'s <a href="youth%20system">youth system</a> and moved to <a href="AIK%20Fotboll%20%28women%29">AIK</a> in summer 2011. She made her debut for AIK as a 15-year-old, in a <a href="Svenska%20Cupen%20%28women%29">Svenska Cupen</a> quarter-final fixture at <a href="Ume%C3%A5%20IK">Umeå IK</a> on 29 March 2015.
She made six appearances in the <a href="2015%20Damallsvenskan">2015 Damallsvenskan</a> for <a href="Promotion%20and%20relegation">relegated</a> AIK, but was given a more central role the following season. In 2016 she scored 15 goals in 20 <a href="Elitettan">Elitettan</a> matches and 20 goals in 23 matches across all competitions. In January 2017 she joined English <a href="FA%20WSL">FA WSL</a> club <a href="Manchester%20City%20W.F.C.">Manchester City</a> on trial, but ultimately re-signed for AIK in time for the 2017 season. In July 2017 she <a href="Transfer%20%28association%20football%29">transferred</a> to Damallsvenskan club <a href="Eskilstuna%20United%20DFF">Eskilstuna United</a>.
On her debut appearance for Eskilstuna United, Kullashi scored two goals in a 4–0 home win over <a href="IF%20Limhamn%20Bunkeflo">IF Limhamn Bunkeflo</a>. She was praised by team mate <a href="Olivia%20Schough">Olivia Schough</a> and her new <a href="Coach%20%28sports%29">coach</a> for her <a href="dribbling">dribbling</a> abilities.
International career.
Kullashi was the youngest player named to the Sweden squad for the <a href="2016%20FIFA%20U-20%20Women%27s%20World%20Cup">2016 FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup</a> in Papua New Guinea.
In January 2018, 18-year-old Kullashi enjoyed a "dream" debut for the senior <a href="Sweden%20women%27s%20national%20football%20team">Sweden</a> team, scoring two goals in a 3–0 win over <a href="South%20Africa%20women%27s%20national%20football%20team">South Africa</a>.
